ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, the sucrose stock solution and H3PO4 used for the study have showed no significant emission of fluorescence when they are separately excited at 423nm. However, once the two solutions were combined and incubated in the oven, light brownish solution was formed and fluorescence emission was detectable when excited at 423nm (Fig. 1
                        ). This observation matches well with previous works that synthesised CDs via carbonisation of sucrose using H3PO4 
                        [33]. H3PO4 under mild heated condition has the power to hydrolyse organic compounds into simple molecules rich with carbon. Sugar is a carbohydrate and when water was removed in this elimination reaction, it basically left with elemental carbon. The expected exothermic reaction during the hydrolysis process can cause the polymerisation of the carbon residues to occur and subsequently forming small carbon particles. In this case, the dehydration power of H3PO4 is milder when compared to other strong acid such as sulfuric acid and this can promote better particle growth over nucleation. This seems to support the observation on the red-shifting of fluorescence from the commonly recorded fluorescence of CDs that is often in the blue and UV regions.

The purified and lyophilised CDs were re-dispersed in ultrapure water and the fluorescence was found to be effected by the presence of acetone. This was identified in the initial trial study where the intensity has shown an increment on the first addition of paraoxon-ethyl in acetone before showing a quenching trend with the subsequent addition. Further study with the addition of 100μL of pure acetone into the CDs solution has proven that the signal has increased by approximately 10% due to the acetone (Fig. 5
                        ). This was not uncommon as it can be due to the change in the solvent property that subsequently affecting the fluorescence efficiency. This effect need to be addressed as the paraoxon-ethyl is acetone soluble and will be introduced to the CDs directly in acetone as solvent. In order to normalise the fluorescence signal, preconditioning of the CDs solution was performed by first adding in 1:1 ratio of acetone prior to the analytical analysis. It was found that further addition of acetone up to 400μL in volume has no significant effect on the baseline signal and the detection probe was ready to be used (inset, Fig. 5
                        ). The precondition has solved the issue of intensity increment for the first addition of paraoxon-ethyl sample.

The evaluation of the sensing signal was performed by taking the largest signal change caused by the paraoxon-ethyl within the wavelength window, which has been identified at 524nm (Fig. 7
                        ). Thus, subsequent calibration curve was constructed based on the unit of fluorescence quenching at 524nm (ΔI) upon addition of known concentration of paraoxon-ethyl. A linear plot was obtained up to the concentration of 5.80mM (inset Fig. 7) with a linear correlation relationship of ΔI=39258[paraoxon-ethyl]+3.2112, and a R2 value of 0.9974. The limit of detection (LOD) for the proposed detection probe was evaluated to be 0.22±0.02μM using the standard 3σ/s method, where σ is the standard deviation of blank signal (n=6) and s is the slope of the calibration. This is equivalent to the capability to detect concentration down to the lowest limit of 0.061±0.006ppm, a level lower than the general legal limit of 0.100ppm allowed in surface wastewaters [37]. This analytical performance is comparable with some other sensing systems reported on the sensing of paraoxon pesticide as shown in Table 1
                        . Thus the method might be able to serve an alarm for the monitoring of paraoxon-ethyl in waste water as well, besides vegetables as focused in this study. Often, the allowable limit in drinking water is also around sub-ppm level for organophosphate pesticides. Thus, this probe might have real potential to be further adopted into water quality monitoring for drinking water, besides the monitoring of agricultural products such as the vegetables as demonstrated in this work. This can be targeted especially for third world countries with less resource, but of high risk of exposure due to the agricultural activities.
